{"title_page": "Basilica of The National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima (Lewiston New York)", "text_new": ":''For the Basilica in [[F\u00e1tima, Portugal]], please see'': [[Our Lady of F\u00e1tima Basilica]]\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox church\n| denomination = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| name = Basilica of The National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima\n| img = Basilica Lewiston NY.jpg\n| caption = Basilica of The National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima\n| coordinates =  {{coord|43|12|0.5538|N|79|0|17.03|W}}\n| country = United States\n| location = [[Lewiston, NY]]\n| tradition = [[Latin Church|Latin Rite]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.fatimashrine.com/|National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima}}\n| dedication = [[Mary, Mother of Jesus|Blessed Virgin Mary]]\n| dedicated date = 1965\n| status = [[Minor basilica]]\n| functional status = Active\n| architect = \n| architectural type = [[Church (building)|Church]]\n| style = [[Church_architecture#Modernism|Modernism]]\n| length = \n| diocese = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo|Buffalo, New York]]\n| bishop = [[Sede vacante]]\n| rector = [[http://www.barnabites.com/|The Barnabite Fathers]]\n}}\nThe '''Basilica of the National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima''' is a [[Church_architecture#Modernism|Modernist]] [[Minor basilica]] and [[National Shrine|US National Shrine]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]], honoring the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]] as [[Our lady of fatima|Our Lady of Fatima]], the [[Patroness]] of the [[United States]]. The shrine is directed by The [[Barnabite| Barnabite Fathers]].  It is located at 1023 Swann Road in [[Lewiston, NY|Lewiston, New York, USA]], north of [[Niagara Falls]].<ref>{{cite web |title=National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima |url=https://thecatholictravelguide.com/destinations/u-s-a/buffalo-new-york-catholic-shrines-places-of-interest/lewiston-new-york-basilica-national-shrine-lady-fatima/ |website=Catholic Travel Guide |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn the mid-1950s the Catholic Polish and Italian communities in the Niagara Falls region joined together. They sought to support the Barnabite Fathers, a missionary order working the area.  The group set out to create a shrine dedicated to Our Lady of Fatima.\n\nFirst among the many Shrine benefactors were Mr. & Mrs. Walter Ciurzak who, in 1954, donated {{convert|16|acre|m2}} of their farmland for the construction of the Shrine.  \nin Lewiston.  At that time, the shrine began with just one humble statue of Our Lady of Fatima. Later, in 1960, the shrine that exists today was founded.<ref name=\"Donor\">[http://www.fatimashrine.com/ Official Web Site]</ref>\n\nThe church was started in 1963 and dedicated in 1965.\n\nOn October 7, 1975 [[Paul VI|Pope Paul VI]] conferred the title of [[Basilica]] upon the church.  Thousands of [[pilgrimage|pilgrims]] from around the country and the world visit the basilica each year.\n\n==Notable Features==\n\nThe basilica is located on 16 acres of land. The Basilica is highlighted by a magnificent dome that measures {{convert|100|ft|m}} in diameter and {{convert|55|ft|m|adj=on}} high.  The dome is covered with two layers of glass and [[acrylic glass]] depicting a contour of the [[Northern hemisphere]]. On top of the dome, there is a statue of [[Our Lady of Fatima]] which is {{convert|13|ft|m}} high and weighs 10 tons, sculpted from [[Vermont]] granite.\n\nA {{convert|48|ft|m|adj=on}}-tall bell tower was built during the 25th anniversary year, 1981, and is dedicated to the memory of Barnabite Father Charles M. Barlassina, who served at the shrine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Catholic Travel Guide |url=https://thecatholictravelguide.com/destinations/u-s-a/buffalo-new-york-catholic-shrines-places-of-interest/lewiston-new-york-basilica-national-shrine-lady-fatima/ |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther highlights include:\n\n* A [[Shrine]] of [[Anthony Maria Zaccaria|St. Anthony Mary Zaccari]]\n* The Little Chapel of Fatima\n* The Avenue of [[Saints#Roman Catholicism|Saints]], where over one hundred life-size marble statues represent Saints from every race and walk of life are featured.\n* A Shrine of [[Mother Cabrini]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima |url=https://exploringupstate.com/basilica-of-the-national-shrine-of-our-lady-of-fatima/ |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Renovation==\n\nIn 2008, a $6 million renovation was undertaken.  It was the first major renovation and addition in over fifty years. The rector, Father Julio Ciavaglia of the Barnibite Fathers, collaborated with architects for the design of 7,400 sq.ft. of additional space.  The overall focus for this work brings the old world artisan experience with the use of granite stone walls, arched doorways, stained glass windows, structural wood beams and copper roofs to the shrine.\n\nThe renovation included a new ambulatory space around the front entrance to provide a separation between the main domed basilica and the exterior. This space provides an area for visitors to experience the basilica and the adjoining chapels without interrupting an ongoing service. The existing Sacristy along the rear of the building was removed and replaced with a 2,260 sq. ft. addition for small gatherings and to show the historical compilation of religious relics that have been collected by the Barnibite Fathers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shrine Renovation |url=http://www.lauer-manguso.com/Tools/Portfolio/frontend/item.asp?type=28&size=0&lngDisplay=0&jPageNumber=3&strMetaTag= |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Catholic basilicas]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo]]\n*[[Barnabites]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fatimashrine.com/ Official Web Site]\n* [https://www.barnabites.com/fatimashrineny Our Lady of Fatima Shrine Page at Barnabite Fathers website]\n* [https://www.iloveny.com/listing/our-lady-of-fatima-shrine/3028/ Our Lady of Fatima Shrine Page at New York Department of Economic Development website]\n\n{{Our Lady of F\u00e1tima|state=uncollapsed}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo|https://www.buffalodiocese.org/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basilica of the National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima Lewiston, NY}}\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic church buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1965]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Marian shrines]]\n[[Category:Basilica churches in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": ":''For the Basilica in [[F\u00e1tima, Portugal]], please see'': [[Our Lady of F\u00e1tima Basilica]]\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox church\n| denomination = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| name = Basilica of The National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima\n| img = Basilica Lewiston NY.jpg\n| caption = Basilica of The National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima\n| coordinates =  {{coord|43|12|0.5538|N|79|0|17.03|W}}\n| country = United States\n| location = [[Lewiston, NY]]\n| tradition = [[Latin Church|Latin Rite]]\n| website = {{URL|http://http://www.fatimashrine.com/|National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima}}\n| dedication = [[Mary, Mother of Jesus|Blessed Virgin Mary]]\n| dedicated date = 1965\n| status = [[Minor basilica]]\n| functional status = Active\n| architect = \n| architectural type = [[Church (building)|Church]]\n| style = [[Church_architecture#Modernism|Modernism]]\n| length = \n| diocese = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo|Buffalo, New York]]\n| bishop = [[Sede vacante]]\n| rector = [[http://www.barnabites.com/|The Barnabite Fathers]]\n}}\nThe '''Basilica of the National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima''' is a [[Church_architecture#Modernism|Modernist]] [[Minor basilica]] and [[National Shrine|US National Shrine]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]], honoring the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]] as [[Our lady of fatima|Our Lady of Fatima]], the [[Patroness]] of the [[United States]]. The shrine is directed by The [[Barnabite| Barnabite Fathers]].  It is located at 1023 Swann Road in [[Lewiston, NY|Lewiston, New York, USA]], north of [[Niagara Falls]].<ref>{{cite web |title=National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima |url=https://thecatholictravelguide.com/destinations/u-s-a/buffalo-new-york-catholic-shrines-places-of-interest/lewiston-new-york-basilica-national-shrine-lady-fatima/ |website=Catholic Travel Guide |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn the mid-1950s the Catholic Polish and Italian communities in the Niagara Falls region joined together. They sought to support the Barnabite Fathers, a missionary order working the area.  The group set out to create a shrine dedicated to Our Lady of Fatima.\n\nFirst among the many Shrine benefactors were Mr. & Mrs. Walter Ciurzak who, in 1954, donated {{convert|16|acre|m2}} of their farmland for the construction of the Shrine.  \nin Lewiston.  At that time, the shrine began with just one humble statue of Our Lady of Fatima. Later, in 1960, the shrine that exists today was founded.<ref name=\"Donor\">[http://www.fatimashrine.com/ Official Web Site]</ref>\n\nThe church was started in 1963 and dedicated in 1965.\n\nOn October 7, 1975 [[Paul VI|Pope Paul VI]] conferred the title of [[Basilica]] upon the church.  Thousands of [[pilgrimage|pilgrims]] from around the country and the world visit the basilica each year.\n\n==Notable Features==\n\nThe basilica is located on 16 acres of land. The Basilica is highlighted by a magnificent dome that measures {{convert|100|ft|m}} in diameter and {{convert|55|ft|m|adj=on}} high.  The dome is covered with two layers of glass and [[acrylic glass]] depicting a contour of the [[Northern hemisphere]]. On top of the dome, there is a statue of [[Our Lady of Fatima]] which is {{convert|13|ft|m}} high and weighs 10 tons, sculpted from [[Vermont]] granite.\n\nA {{convert|48|ft|m|adj=on}}-tall bell tower was built during the 25th anniversary year, 1981, and is dedicated to the memory of Barnabite Father Charles M. Barlassina, who served at the shrine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Catholic Travel Guide |url=https://thecatholictravelguide.com/destinations/u-s-a/buffalo-new-york-catholic-shrines-places-of-interest/lewiston-new-york-basilica-national-shrine-lady-fatima/ |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther highlights include:\n\n* A [[Shrine]] of [[Anthony Maria Zaccaria|St. Anthony Mary Zaccari]]\n* The Little Chapel of Fatima\n* The Avenue of [[Saints#Roman Catholicism|Saints]], where over one hundred life-size marble statues represent Saints from every race and walk of life are featured.\n* A Shrine of [[Mother Cabrini]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima |url=https://exploringupstate.com/basilica-of-the-national-shrine-of-our-lady-of-fatima/ |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Renovation==\n\nIn 2008, a $6 million renovation was undertaken.  It was the first major renovation and addition in over fifty years. The rector, Father Julio Ciavaglia of the Barnibite Fathers, collaborated with architects for the design of 7,400 sq.ft. of additional space.  The overall focus for this work brings the old world artisan experience with the use of granite stone walls, arched doorways, stained glass windows, structural wood beams and copper roofs to the shrine.\n\nThe renovation included a new ambulatory space around the front entrance to provide a separation between the main domed basilica and the exterior. This space provides an area for visitors to experience the basilica and the adjoining chapels without interrupting an ongoing service. The existing Sacristy along the rear of the building was removed and replaced with a 2,260 sq. ft. addition for small gatherings and to show the historical compilation of religious relics that have been collected by the Barnibite Fathers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shrine Renovation |url=http://www.lauer-manguso.com/Tools/Portfolio/frontend/item.asp?type=28&size=0&lngDisplay=0&jPageNumber=3&strMetaTag= |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Catholic basilicas]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo]]\n*[[Barnabites]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fatimashrine.com/ Official Web Site]\n* [https://www.barnabites.com/fatimashrineny Our Lady of Fatima Shrine Page at Barnabite Fathers website]\n* [https://www.iloveny.com/listing/our-lady-of-fatima-shrine/3028/ Our Lady of Fatima Shrine Page at New York Department of Economic Development website]\n\n{{Our Lady of F\u00e1tima|state=uncollapsed}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo|https://www.buffalodiocese.org/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basilica of the National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima Lewiston, NY}}\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic church buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1965]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Marian shrines]]\n[[Category:Basilica churches in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "http", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basilica_of_The_National_Shrine_of_Our_Lady_of_Fatima_(Lewiston_New_York)"}
{"title_page": "Sergey Spivak", "text_new": "{{short description|Moldovan mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Sergey Spivak\n| image           =\n| image_size      = \n| other_names     = Polar Bear\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|1|24}}\n| birth_place     = [[Chisinau]], Moldova \n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     = [[Moldova]]n\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Serghei Spivac |url=https://www.ufc.com/athlete/serghei-spivac |website=UFC.com |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n| weight          = {{convert|260|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Serghei Spivac |url=https://www.ufc.com/athlete/serghei-spivac |website=UFC.com |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n| weight_class    = [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]]<br>\n| reach_in        = 78\n| style           = \n| stance          = Orthodox\n| fighting_out_of = Chisinau, Moldova\n| team            = MIR Production<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak |url=https://www.themmaway.com/fighter/Sergey-Spivak |website=The MMA Way |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n| trainers         =\n| years_active    = 2014\u2013present\n| mma_kowin       = 4\n| mma_subwin      = 6\n| mma_decwin      = 0\n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_decloss     = 1\n| mma_nc          = \n| sherdog         = 179095\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''Sergey Spivak''' (born 24 January 1995) is a Moldovan [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] who competes in the [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] division of the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]. A professional competitor since 2014, he has also formerly competed for World Warriors Fighting Championships, Eagles Fighting Championship, N1 Pro Nomad MMA and Real Fight Promotion.\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n\n===Early career===\nSergey Spivak made his MMA debut in the September of 2014 with the Ukrainian promotion Real Fight Promotion, at 19 years old. He faced Andrey Serebrianikov as his first opponent. He won the fight in the last minute of the first round, by way of TKO.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak vs Andrey Serebrianikov |url=https://www.mma-core.com/fights/Sergey_Spivak_vs_Andrey_Serebrianikov/1316079 |website=MMA-Core.com |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis second fight was with the Ukrainian based World Warriors Fighting Championships, at WWFC Ukraine Selection 1, where he faced  Evgeniy Bova in the main event. Spivak won the fight in the first round by way of a kimura.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak vs. Evgeniy Bova |url=https://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/181006-wwfc-sergey-polar-bear-spivak-vs-evgeniy-bova |website=Tapology |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis second fight with World Warriors Fighting Championships was during WWFC: Ukraine Selection 4, in the main event. His opponent was  Yuri Gorbenko, whom he defeated in the first round through an armbar.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yuri Gorbenko vs. Sergey Spivak |url=https://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/180996-wwfc-sergey-polar-bear-spivak-vs-yuri-gorbenko |website=Tapology |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpivak would than fight against Dimitriy Mikutsa, under the N1 Pro organization. Spivak submitted Mikutsa through an armbar during the last minute of the second round.\n\nUnder the banner of Eagles Fighting Championship, Spivak faced Artem Cherkov. He would beat him in the first round, by way of a head kick.<ref>{{cite web |title=Artem Cherkov vs. Sergey Spivak |url=https://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/246851-eagles-fighting-championship-1-artem-cherkov-vs-sergey-polar-bear-spivak |website=Tapology |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year-long layoff, Spivak would return to the World Warriors Fighting Championships. His first opponent was Luke Morton, whom he beat by KO. In his next fight Spivak fought against the MMA veteran [[Travis Fulton]] for the vacant WWFC Heavyweight Championship, a fight which he won in the first round by a rear naked choke. He would defend the title 10 months later against the Croatian fighter Ivo Cuk, winning the bout in the first round by TKO. His last fight with WWFC was his last title defense, five months after his fight with Cuk, against Tony Lopez. He defeated Lopez by a neck crank  in the last minute of the first round.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak |url=https://mmadna.nl/ufc-fighters/sergey-spivak/ |website=MMA DNA |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nSpivak made his UFC debut during [[UFC Fight Night 151]], at 23 years old, against [[Walt Harris (fighter)|Walt Harris]], replacing [[Aleksei Oleinik]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/4/9/18303630/unbeaten-sergey-spivak-steps-in-to-fight-walt-harris-at-ufc-ottawa|title=Unbeaten Sergey Spivak steps in to fight Walt Harris at UFC Ottawa|last=Lee|first=Alexander K.|date=2019-04-09|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>  He suffered the first professional loss of his career. Harris pushed Sergey up to the cage, dazed him with a left straight and dropped him to the floor with a barrage of knees. After a series of grounded strikes, the referee awarded Harris a win, after 50 seconds, by way of TKO.<ref>{{cite web |title=UFC Ottawa Results: Walt Harris Runs Through Sergey Spivak |url=https://cagesidepress.com/2019/05/04/ufc-ottawa-results-walt-harris-sergey-spivac/ |website=Cage Side Press |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nFive months later, Spivak fought against [[Tai Tuivasa]]at [[UFC 243]].<ref name=\"UFC243\">{{Cite web|url=https://mmadna.nl/tuivasa-vs-spivak-en-kassem-vs-kim-toegevoegd-aan-ufc-243-in-melbourne/|title=Tuivasa vs. Spivak en Kassem vs. Kim toegevoegd aan UFC 243 in Melbourne|last=DNA|first=MMA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> Spivak would begin the fight with a series of leg kicks which dropped Tuivasa, following him down and looking for ground and pound. Whenever the Australian would return to his feet, Spivak would pursue takedowns. The fight ended in the fourth minute of the second round, Spivak winning by an arm triangle choke, awarding him his first UFC win.<ref>{{cite web |title=UFC 243 results: Sergey Spivak batters, bloodies and chokes out Tai Tuivasa |url=https://www.mmamania.com/2019/10/5/20900798/ufc-243-results-sergey-spivak-tai-tuivasa-fight-submission-triangle-heavyweight-melbourne-mma |website=MMA Mania |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpivak faced [[Marcin Tybura]] on February 29, 2020 at [[UFC Fight Night 169]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/01/ufc-on-espn-plus-27-norfolk-bouts-added-serghei-spivac-marcin-tybura|title=Three bouts added to growing UFC on ESPN+ 27 lineup|website=www.mmajunkie.com|author=Nolan King|date=2020-01-02|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> He lost the fight via unanimous decision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2020/02/29/ufc-norfolk-results-marcin-tybura-uses-heavy-wrestling-gameplan-get-past-sergey-spivak/|title=UFC Norfolk Results: Marcin Tybura beats Sergey Spivak by Decision|last=Shillan|first=Keith|date=2020-02-29|website=Cageside Press|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\nSpivak is expected to face Carlos Felipe on May 9, 2020 at [[UFC 250]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/combate/noticia/ultimate-encaminha-duelo-entre-carlos-boi-e-sergey-spivak-para-o-ufc-250-em-sao-paulo.ghtml|title=UFC sets fight between Carlos Boi and Sergey Spivak at UFC 250 in S\u00e3o Paulo|website=sportv.globo.com|author=Marcelo Barone|date=2020-03-05|access-date=2020-03-05}} {{in lang|pt}}</ref> However, on April 9, [[Dana White]], the president of UFC announced that this event was postponed to a future date<ref name=\"Postpone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29018339/dana-white-says-ufc-249-not-happen-april-18|title=Dana White says UFC 249 will not happen April 18|publisher=espn.com|author=Brett Okamoto|date=2020-04-09|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n\n===Mixed martial arts===\n*'''WWFC'''\n**WWFC Heavyweight Championship (One time)<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak: \"My time will come soon!\" |url=https://wwfc.ua/en/news/sergey-spivak-skoro-nastupit-moye-vremya-/ |website=WWFC |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n***Two successful title defenses\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n|ko-wins=4\n|sub-wins=6\n|dec-wins=0\n|ko-losses=1\n|sub-losses=0\n|dec-losses=1\n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|align=center|10\u20132\n|[[Marcin Tybura]]\n|Decision (unanimous)\n|[[UFC Fight Night: Benavidez vs. Figueiredo]] \n|{{dts|format=dmy|2020|February|29}}\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|5:00\n|[[Norfolk, Virginia]], United States\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|10\u20131\n|[[Tai Tuivasa]]\n|Submission (arm-triangle choke)\n|[[UFC 243]]\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2019|October|5}}\n|align=Center|2\n|align*center|3:14\n|[[Melbourne]], Australia\n|\n|-\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|align=center|9\u20131\n|[[Walt Harris (fighter)|Walt Harris]]\n|TKO (punches)\n|[[UFC Fight Night: Iaquinta vs. Cowboy]]\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2019|May|4}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|0:50\n|[[Ontario]], Canada\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|9\u20130\n|Tony Lopez\n|Submission (neck crank)\n|WWFC 12\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|September|29}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|4:12\n|[[Kiev]], Ukraine\n|{{small|Defended the WWFC Heavyweight Championship.}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|8\u20130\n|Ivo Cuk\n|TKO (punches)\n|WWFC 10\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|March|24}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|2:21\n|[[Kiev]], Ukraine\n|{{small|Defended the WWFC Heavyweight Championship.}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|7\u20130\n|[[Travis Fulton]]\n|Submission (rear-naked choke)\n|WWFC - Cage Encounter 7\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2017|June|14}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|2:50\n|[[Kiev]], Ukraine\n|{{small|For the vacant WWFC Heavyweight Championship}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|6\u20130\n|Luke Morton\n|KO (punches)\n|WWFC - Cage Encounter 6\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2017|March|29}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|0:40\n|[[Kiev]], Ukraine\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|5\u20130\n|Artem Cherkov\n|KO (head kick)\n|Eagles Fighting Championship\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2016|February|27}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|1:52\n|[[Chisinau]], Moldova\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|4\u20130\n|Dimitriy Mikutsa\n|Submission (armbar)\n|N1 Pro - MMA Nomad\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2015|October|4}}\n|align=Center|2\n|align*center|4:34\n|[[Karaganda]], Kazakhstan \n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|3\u20130\n|Yuri Gorbenko\n|Submission (armbar)\n|WWFC - Ukraine Selection 4\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2015|January|31}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|3:38\n|[[Kiev]], Ukraine\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|2\u20130\n|Evgeniy Bova\n|Submission (kimura)\n|WWFC - Ukraine Selection 1\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2014|November|19}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|?:??\n|[[Lviv]], Ukraine\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|1\u20130\n|Andrey Serebrianikov\n|TKO (punches)\n|RFP - Galychyny Cup\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2014|September|28}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|4:31\n|[[Lviv]], Ukraine\n|\n|-\n{{end}}\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Ciryl Gane |url=https://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Ciryl-Gane-293973 |website=Sherdog |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of current UFC fighters]]\n*[[List of male mixed martial artists]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spivak, Sergey}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chi\u0219in\u0103u]]\n[[Category:Moldovan male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Moldovan sambo practitioners]]\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship male fighters]]\n[[Category:Heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Moldovan mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Sergey Spivak\n| image           =\n| image_size      = \n| other_names     = Polar Bear\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|1|24}}\n| birth_place     = [[Chisinau]], Moldova \n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     = [[Moldova]]n\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Serghei Spivac |url=https://www.ufc.com/athlete/serghei-spivac |website=UFC.com |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n| weight          = {{convert|260|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Serghei Spivac |url=https://www.ufc.com/athlete/serghei-spivac |website=UFC.com |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n| weight_class    = [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]]<br>\n| reach_in        = 78\n| style           = \n| stance          = Orthodox\n| fighting_out_of = Chisinau, Moldova\n| team            = MIR Production<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak |url=https://www.themmaway.com/fighter/Sergey-Spivak |website=The MMA Way |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n| trainers         =\n| years_active    = 2014\u2013present\n| mma_kowin       = 4\n| mma_subwin      = 6\n| mma_decwin      = 0\n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_decloss     = 1\n| mma_nc          = \n| sherdog         = 179095\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n'''Sergey Spivak''' (born 24 Januray 1995) is a Moldovan [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] who competes in the [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] division of the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]. A professional competitor since 2014, he has also formerly competed for World Warriors Fighting Championships, Eagles Fighting Championship, N1 Pro Nomad MMA and Real Fight Promotion.\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n\n===Early career===\nSergey Spivak made his MMA debut in the September of 2014 with the Ukrainian promotion Real Fight Promotion, at 19 years old. He faced Andrey Serebrianikov as his first opponent. He won the fight in the last minute of the first round, by way of TKO.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak vs Andrey Serebrianikov |url=https://www.mma-core.com/fights/Sergey_Spivak_vs_Andrey_Serebrianikov/1316079 |website=MMA-Core.com |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis second fight was with the Ukrainian based World Warriors Fighting Championships, at WWFC Ukraine Selection 1, where he faced  Evgeniy Bova in the main event. Spivak won the fight in the first round by way of a kimura.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak vs. Evgeniy Bova |url=https://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/181006-wwfc-sergey-polar-bear-spivak-vs-evgeniy-bova |website=Tapology |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis second fight with World Warriors Fighting Championships was during WWFC: Ukraine Selection 4, in the main event. His opponent was  Yuri Gorbenko, whom he defeated in the first round through an armbar.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yuri Gorbenko vs. Sergey Spivak |url=https://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/180996-wwfc-sergey-polar-bear-spivak-vs-yuri-gorbenko |website=Tapology |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpivak would than fight against Dimitriy Mikutsa, under the N1 Pro organization. Spivak submitted Mikutsa through an armbar during the last minute of the second round.\n\nUnder the banner of Eagles Fighting Championship, Spivak faced Artem Cherkov. He would beat him in the first round, by way of a head kick.<ref>{{cite web |title=Artem Cherkov vs. Sergey Spivak |url=https://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/246851-eagles-fighting-championship-1-artem-cherkov-vs-sergey-polar-bear-spivak |website=Tapology |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year-long layoff, Spivak would return to the World Warriors Fighting Championships. His first opponent was Luke Morton, whom he beat by KO. In his next fight Spivak fought against the MMA veteran [[Travis Fulton]] for the vacant WWFC Heavyweight Championship, a fight which he won in the first round by a rear naked choke. He would defend the title 10 months later against the Croatian fighter Ivo Cuk, winning the bout in the first round by TKO. His last fight with WWFC was his last title defense, five months after his fight with Cuk, against Tony Lopez. He defeated Lopez by a neck crank  in the last minute of the first round.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak |url=https://mmadna.nl/ufc-fighters/sergey-spivak/ |website=MMA DNA |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nSpivak made his UFC debut during [[UFC Fight Night 151]], at 23 years old, against [[Walt Harris (fighter)|Walt Harris]], replacing [[Aleksei Oleinik]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/4/9/18303630/unbeaten-sergey-spivak-steps-in-to-fight-walt-harris-at-ufc-ottawa|title=Unbeaten Sergey Spivak steps in to fight Walt Harris at UFC Ottawa|last=Lee|first=Alexander K.|date=2019-04-09|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>  He suffered the first professional loss of his career. Harris pushed Sergey up to the cage, dazed him with a left straight and dropped him to the floor with a barrage of knees. After a series of grounded strikes, the referee awarded Harris a win, after 50 seconds, by way of TKO.<ref>{{cite web |title=UFC Ottawa Results: Walt Harris Runs Through Sergey Spivak |url=https://cagesidepress.com/2019/05/04/ufc-ottawa-results-walt-harris-sergey-spivac/ |website=Cage Side Press |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nFive months later, Spivak fought against [[Tai Tuivasa]]at [[UFC 243]].<ref name=\"UFC243\">{{Cite web|url=https://mmadna.nl/tuivasa-vs-spivak-en-kassem-vs-kim-toegevoegd-aan-ufc-243-in-melbourne/|title=Tuivasa vs. Spivak en Kassem vs. Kim toegevoegd aan UFC 243 in Melbourne|last=DNA|first=MMA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> Spivak would begin the fight with a series of leg kicks which dropped Tuivasa, following him down and looking for ground and pound. Whenever the Australian would return to his feet, Spivak would pursue takedowns. The fight ended in the fourth minute of the second round, Spivak winning by an arm triangle choke, awarding him his first UFC win.<ref>{{cite web |title=UFC 243 results: Sergey Spivak batters, bloodies and chokes out Tai Tuivasa |url=https://www.mmamania.com/2019/10/5/20900798/ufc-243-results-sergey-spivak-tai-tuivasa-fight-submission-triangle-heavyweight-melbourne-mma |website=MMA Mania |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpivak faced [[Marcin Tybura]] on February 29, 2020 at [[UFC Fight Night 169]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/01/ufc-on-espn-plus-27-norfolk-bouts-added-serghei-spivac-marcin-tybura|title=Three bouts added to growing UFC on ESPN+ 27 lineup|website=www.mmajunkie.com|author=Nolan King|date=2020-01-02|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> He lost the fight via unanimous decision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2020/02/29/ufc-norfolk-results-marcin-tybura-uses-heavy-wrestling-gameplan-get-past-sergey-spivak/|title=UFC Norfolk Results: Marcin Tybura beats Sergey Spivak by Decision|last=Shillan|first=Keith|date=2020-02-29|website=Cageside Press|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\nSpivak is expected to face Carlos Felipe on May 9, 2020 at [[UFC 250]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/combate/noticia/ultimate-encaminha-duelo-entre-carlos-boi-e-sergey-spivak-para-o-ufc-250-em-sao-paulo.ghtml|title=UFC sets fight between Carlos Boi and Sergey Spivak at UFC 250 in S\u00e3o Paulo|website=sportv.globo.com|author=Marcelo Barone|date=2020-03-05|access-date=2020-03-05}} {{in lang|pt}}</ref> However, on April 9, [[Dana White]], the president of UFC announced that this event was postponed to a future date<ref name=\"Postpone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29018339/dana-white-says-ufc-249-not-happen-april-18|title=Dana White says UFC 249 will not happen April 18|publisher=espn.com|author=Brett Okamoto|date=2020-04-09|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n\n===Mixed martial arts===\n*'''WWFC'''\n**WWFC Heavyweight Championship (One time)<ref>{{cite web |title=Sergey Spivak: \"My time will come soon!\" |url=https://wwfc.ua/en/news/sergey-spivak-skoro-nastupit-moye-vremya-/ |website=WWFC |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n***Two successful title defenses\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n|ko-wins=4\n|sub-wins=6\n|dec-wins=0\n|ko-losses=1\n|sub-losses=0\n|dec-losses=1\n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|align=center|10\u20132\n|[[Marcin Tybura]]\n|Decision (unanimous)\n|[[UFC Fight Night: Benavidez vs. Figueiredo]] \n|{{dts|format=dmy|2020|February|29}}\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|5:00\n|[[Norfolk, Virginia]], United States\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|10\u20131\n|[[Tai Tuivasa]]\n|Submission (arm-triangle choke)\n|[[UFC 243]]\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2019|October|5}}\n|align=Center|2\n|align*center|3:14\n|[[Melbourne]], Australia\n|\n|-\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|align=center|9\u20131\n|[[Walt Harris (fighter)|Walt Harris]]\n|TKO (punches)\n|[[UFC Fight Night: Iaquinta vs. Cowboy]]\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2019|May|4}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|0:50\n|[[Ontario]], Canada\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|9\u20130\n|Tony Lopez\n|Submission (neck crank)\n|WWFC 12\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|September|29}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|4:12\n|[[Kiev]], Ukraine\n|{{small|Defended the WWFC Heavyweight Championship.}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|8\u20130\n|Ivo Cuk\n|TKO (punches)\n|WWFC 10\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|March|24}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|2:21\n|[[Kiev]], Ukraine\n|{{small|Defended the WWFC Heavyweight Championship.}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|7\u20130\n|[[Travis Fulton]]\n|Submission (rear-naked choke)\n|WWFC - Cage Encounter 7\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2017|June|14}}\n|align=Center|1\n|align*center|2:50\n|[[Kiev]], Ukraine\n|{{small|